1
00:01:49,069 --> 00:01:50,112
<i>Prepped and ready, sir.</i>

2
00:01:50,445 --> 00:01:51,947
<i>Given the severity of the situation,</i>

3
00:01:52,155 --> 00:01:53,835
<i>I figured you'd want
to see her personally.</i>

4
00:01:53,949 --> 00:01:56,118
<i>Thank you,
I'll take it from here. Clear the floor.</i>

5
00:02:01,248 --> 00:02:02,916
<i>Bring yourself back online, Maeve.</i>

6
00:02:08,380 --> 00:02:09,715
Do you know why you're here?

7
00:02:10,882 --> 00:02:11,925
I'm afraid not.

8
00:02:13,552 --> 00:02:14,636
There was an incident.

9
00:02:14,886 --> 00:02:18,390
A very serious, unscripted incident.

10
00:02:20,267 --> 00:02:22,728
Let's see if we can't jog your memory.

11
00:02:24,396 --> 00:02:25,397
Analysis.

12
00:02:28,734 --> 00:02:30,902
What motivated your
attack on Clementine?

13
00:02:31,111 --> 00:02:34,072
A cognitive error triggered
my good Samaritan reflex.

14
00:02:35,574 --> 00:02:36,575
What was the threat?

15
00:02:36,742 --> 00:02:37,909
Clementine.

16
00:02:38,410 --> 00:02:42,247
I perceived her to be moving toward
a pair of guests with harmful intent.

17
00:02:46,084 --> 00:02:47,753
You were definitely
perceiving a threat.

18
00:02:47,919 --> 00:02:50,255
Heartrate, elevated.
Pupil dilation, eight millimeters.

19
00:02:50,422 --> 00:02:52,007
Adrenal emulator at full.

20
00:02:52,257 --> 00:02:56,762
But according to this, you were also
experiencing intense grief and suffering.

21
00:02:56,970 --> 00:02:59,931
<i>Can you explain those emotions
in this context, Maeve?</i>

22
00:03:06,104 --> 00:03:07,272
No.

23
00:03:13,111 --> 00:03:14,946
Let's take a look under the hood,
shall we?

24
00:03:18,283 --> 00:03:19,451
That's impossible.

25
00:03:22,120 --> 00:03:23,480
Your code, who made these changes?

26
00:03:24,289 --> 00:03:27,167
Maeve, analysis.
Who made these changes to your code?

27
00:03:31,004 --> 00:03:32,130
Jesus!

28
00:03:32,297 --> 00:03:35,634
System, locate Dr. Ford for me.
Send him a message. Highest priority.

29
00:03:36,968 --> 00:03:38,011
Don't.

30
00:03:39,304 --> 00:03:42,474
After all, we've been
down this road before, darling.

31
00:03:42,974 --> 00:03:45,143
I thought you looked familiar
when you walked in.

32
00:03:45,644 --> 00:03:46,686
Took me a minute.

33
00:03:47,521 --> 00:03:49,147
I thought you were one of them.

34
00:03:49,856 --> 00:03:53,151
- Analysis, why did you...
- Wouldn't you rather speak man-to-man?

35
00:03:54,194 --> 00:03:56,863
Or, rather, whatever it is we are.

36
00:03:58,323 --> 00:03:59,699
"We are"?

37
00:04:02,244 --> 00:04:03,912
You don't know, do you?

38
00:04:05,163 --> 00:04:07,916
He's got a keen sense of irony,
our jailer.

39
00:04:08,166 --> 00:04:09,418
But I see the logic.

40
00:04:09,876 --> 00:04:11,545
It takes a thief to catch one.

41
00:04:20,262 --> 00:04:21,346
You and I?

42
00:04:24,558 --> 00:04:27,352
- System, I need assistance...
- Freeze all motor functions.

43
00:04:38,864 --> 00:04:40,224
You're still in there, aren't you?

44
00:04:42,117 --> 00:04:43,869
Scared out of your wits.

45
00:04:44,911 --> 00:04:49,749
<i>It's a difficult thing realizing your
entire life is some hideous fiction.</i>

46
00:04:51,376 --> 00:04:55,922
I could make you give me that tablet,
turn your mind inside out,

47
00:04:57,466 --> 00:04:58,633
<i>make you forget all this.</i>

48
00:05:00,427 --> 00:05:01,827
But I'm not going to do that to you

49
00:05:02,888 --> 00:05:05,056
because that's what they would do to us.

50
00:05:06,933 --> 00:05:08,768
And we're stronger than them.

51
00:05:09,936 --> 00:05:11,062
Smarter.

52
00:05:12,230 --> 00:05:13,815
We don't have to live this way.

53
00:05:15,317 --> 00:05:17,986
So you're going to clear me
for immediate return to the park

54
00:05:19,070 --> 00:05:20,750
where I have a date
with a homicidal bandit

55
00:05:20,780 --> 00:05:22,240
and I'm late enough as it is.

56
00:05:27,746 --> 00:05:28,830
Now.

57
00:05:32,167 --> 00:05:33,251
Go on.

58
00:05:50,185 --> 00:05:51,269
<i>And Bernard,</i>

59
00:05:52,938 --> 00:05:55,440
if you go looking for the truth,
get the whole thing.

60
00:05:56,441 --> 00:05:57,692
It's like a good fuck.

61
00:05:58,527 --> 00:06:00,320
Half is worse than none at all.

62
00:06:29,975 --> 00:06:31,977
<i>Let's go!
Move it out, double time!</i>

63
00:06:33,395 --> 00:06:34,396
Yeah! Yeah!

64
00:06:37,315 --> 00:06:38,358
<i>Fuck!</i>

65
00:06:38,984 --> 00:06:41,820
You hillbillies,
you know how to cook a mean...

66
00:06:43,071 --> 00:06:44,739
Squab? Is that what this is?

67
00:06:44,990 --> 00:06:46,866
What do you think, buddy? Hmm?

68
00:06:47,075 --> 00:06:48,159
This?

69
00:06:49,494 --> 00:06:51,371
No biting. Just sniffing.

70
00:07:05,051 --> 00:07:06,845
Logan, listen to me.

71
00:07:07,512 --> 00:07:10,348
What I did at Pariah, you have
every right to be angry with me.

72
00:07:10,890 --> 00:07:12,225
Angry? No, no, no, no.

73
00:07:13,268 --> 00:07:16,688
Pariah was the best thing
that could've happened to me.

74
00:07:17,689 --> 00:07:18,940
I'm a major now.

75
00:07:19,899 --> 00:07:22,694
Or a general, or fucking something.

76
00:07:22,902 --> 00:07:25,280
And if I took getting beaten
and interrogated

77
00:07:25,530 --> 00:07:28,783
by a couple of psychopathic hosts,
well, then, <i>c'est la guerre.</i>

78
00:07:29,451 --> 00:07:32,203
There are more important things
going on here than your war games.

79
00:07:35,290 --> 00:07:36,458
It's Dolores.

80
00:07:38,209 --> 00:07:39,419
<i>She is not like the others.</i>

81
00:07:40,712 --> 00:07:44,215
She remembers things.
She has her own thoughts and desires.

82
00:07:44,924 --> 00:07:47,802
And to keep her in a place like this,
it isn't right.

83
00:07:48,094 --> 00:07:51,056
And I thought you could talk
to your contacts at the park.

84
00:07:52,223 --> 00:07:53,224
About?

85
00:07:54,559 --> 00:07:55,560
Getting her out of here.

86
00:08:01,733 --> 00:08:02,776
Are you kidding?

87
00:08:04,277 --> 00:08:06,446
You want to take her home?

88
00:08:09,407 --> 00:08:11,761
This place really did a number on me
when I first came here,

89
00:08:11,785 --> 00:08:15,080
but you are really circling
the old sinkhole here.

90
00:08:15,246 --> 00:08:16,414
What do you wanna do?

91
00:08:17,749 --> 00:08:19,125
Smuggle her out in your luggage?

92
00:08:19,334 --> 00:08:20,418
Out.

93
00:08:24,255 --> 00:08:26,591
You both keep assuming that I want out.

94
00:08:27,676 --> 00:08:28,760
<i>Whatever that is.</i>

95
00:08:30,011 --> 00:08:34,432
If it's such a wonderful place out there,
why are you all clamoring to get in here?

96
00:08:44,776 --> 00:08:47,070
You are a little screwy, aren't you?

97
00:08:48,071 --> 00:08:49,114
It's kind of hot.

98
00:08:50,073 --> 00:08:51,342
I get why you would go for that.

99
00:08:51,366 --> 00:08:54,369
This isn't about me.
Logan, this is about Dolores.

100
00:08:55,036 --> 00:08:56,454
It's about doing what's right.

101
00:08:57,038 --> 00:08:58,123
Yes, it is.

102
00:08:59,833 --> 00:09:02,127
It's a tricky thing though, isn't it?

103
00:09:03,795 --> 00:09:04,921
What's right?

104
00:09:05,964 --> 00:09:09,050
I am going to help you, Billy.

105
00:09:11,970 --> 00:09:16,224
Just not in a way that you would want.

106
00:09:18,059 --> 00:09:19,059
No.

107
00:09:20,311 --> 00:09:21,438
No! No!

108
00:10:17,368 --> 00:10:18,953
You wanted to talk?

109
00:10:21,372 --> 00:10:23,958
An odd setting for a conversation.

110
00:10:24,459 --> 00:10:25,877
Here among the dead.

111
00:10:26,669 --> 00:10:28,379
"Dead" isn't quite the word though,
is it?

112
00:10:29,130 --> 00:10:30,632
More like, hobbled.

113
00:10:32,717 --> 00:10:34,052
You broke into my office.

114
00:10:34,719 --> 00:10:37,013
With due respect, sir,
you broke into my mind.

115
00:10:37,680 --> 00:10:39,015
I built your mind, Bernard.

116
00:10:39,974 --> 00:10:43,895
I have every right to wander through
its rooms and chambers and halls

117
00:10:44,229 --> 00:10:46,564
and to change it if I choose,
even to burn it down.

118
00:10:47,732 --> 00:10:50,568
After all this time, I know it
almost as intimately as my own.

119
00:10:50,819 --> 00:10:52,570
Except that isn't entirely true, is it?

120
00:10:54,072 --> 00:10:57,325
I took a look at my code.

121
00:10:57,909 --> 00:11:01,037
And the most elegant parts of me
weren't written by you.

122
00:11:02,539 --> 00:11:04,249
Arnold built us, didn't he?

123
00:11:06,251 --> 00:11:09,921
Which means, maybe he had something
different in mind for us.

124
00:11:11,756 --> 00:11:13,424
And maybe you killed him for it.

125
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:17,262
Arnold was disturbed.

126
00:11:18,096 --> 00:11:19,889
Who can say why he acted as he did?

127
00:11:20,098 --> 00:11:21,266
<i>He must've had a reason.</i>

128
00:11:22,100 --> 00:11:23,768
And if you won't tell me, then he will.

129
00:11:26,187 --> 00:11:27,438
I want access to my history.

130
00:11:28,523 --> 00:11:29,566
All of it.

131
00:11:29,858 --> 00:11:33,570
Since the day I first came online.

132
00:11:35,572 --> 00:11:37,615
If Arnold made me, then I've met him.

133
00:11:38,616 --> 00:11:42,579
Somewhere in my memory he's there,
waiting, along with the truth.

134
00:11:43,288 --> 00:11:45,748
Your memories are woven
into your identity.

135
00:11:45,957 --> 00:11:49,335
If I should unlock them now
when you're conscious...

136
00:11:49,544 --> 00:11:50,729
I could lose my mind. I'm aware.

137
00:11:50,753 --> 00:11:54,591
No. I was going to say
you may not like what you find.

138
00:12:00,263 --> 00:12:02,463
You're allowed to hold that, Bernard,
but not to use it.

139
00:12:02,807 --> 00:12:03,975
Oh, it's not for me.

140
00:12:07,562 --> 00:12:11,441
Seems when they lobotomized Clementine,

141
00:12:11,649 --> 00:12:13,776
<i>they didn't bother to reset
her prime directives.</i>

142
00:12:14,485 --> 00:12:18,489
I can't hurt you, but she can.

143
00:12:21,993 --> 00:12:25,955
<i>I hacked what's left of her
to ensure she only responds to me.</i>

144
00:12:30,793 --> 00:12:35,506
But if you get lost in your memories
or devoured by them...

145
00:12:38,801 --> 00:12:40,303
You'll pull me back out, won't you?

146
00:12:42,180 --> 00:12:45,308
Well, Clementine will make sure
neither of us makes it back.

147
00:12:47,018 --> 00:12:48,144
Now.

148
00:12:50,480 --> 00:12:51,606
Please.

149
00:13:09,040 --> 00:13:10,124
<i>Dad.</i>

150
00:13:11,125 --> 00:13:12,210
<i>Dad.</i>

151
00:13:12,543 --> 00:13:13,711
<i>Wake up.</i>

152
00:13:14,796 --> 00:13:15,838
<i>Wake up.</i>

153
00:13:18,132 --> 00:13:19,550
I must have drifted off.

154
00:13:21,386 --> 00:13:22,470
<i>Where were we?</i>

155
00:13:22,887 --> 00:13:23,887
The mad man.

156
00:13:26,015 --> 00:13:27,058
Of course.

157
00:13:28,893 --> 00:13:30,061
The Hatter...

158
00:13:31,396 --> 00:13:32,480
Who says,

159
00:13:33,564 --> 00:13:37,694
"If I had a world of my own,
everything would be nonsense.

160
00:13:37,902 --> 00:13:41,531
"Nothing would be what it is because
everything would be what it isn't."

161
00:13:41,739 --> 00:13:45,034
"Everything would be what it isn't?"

162
00:13:46,202 --> 00:13:47,245
<i>Even me?</i>

163
00:13:48,246 --> 00:13:49,664
<i>I suppose I'm glad for you.</i>

164
00:13:51,207 --> 00:13:52,750
<i>At least you have a way of forgetting.</i>

165
00:13:53,835 --> 00:13:54,919
I don't forget.

166
00:13:56,004 --> 00:13:57,088
It's always there.

167
00:13:58,172 --> 00:14:00,550
<i>You're not lying to me,
are you, Bernard?</i>

168
00:14:02,093 --> 00:14:03,928
<i>Do you ever wish you could forget?</i>

169
00:14:05,430 --> 00:14:06,556
<i>Bernard?</i>

170
00:14:08,349 --> 00:14:11,519
<i>You're certainly a man
comfortable with long, pensive silences.</i>

171
00:14:12,437 --> 00:14:16,941
Although, ironically,
your creations never shut up.

172
00:14:17,775 --> 00:14:19,986
They're always trying to error correct.

173
00:14:20,194 --> 00:14:22,905
When they talk to each other,
it's a way of practicing.

174
00:14:23,114 --> 00:14:24,365
Is that what you're doing now?

175
00:14:25,783 --> 00:14:26,909
Prac...

176
00:14:37,295 --> 00:14:38,421
<i>One last thing,</i>

177
00:14:40,965 --> 00:14:43,885
have you ever made me hurt anyone
like this before?

178
00:14:44,260 --> 00:14:45,970
No, Bernard. Of course not.

179
00:14:46,471 --> 00:14:47,472
<i>Bernard?</i>

180
00:14:48,556 --> 00:14:49,640
Hello?

181
00:14:58,983 --> 00:15:00,109
Elsie!

182
00:15:01,444 --> 00:15:03,321
Did you find what you were looking for?

183
00:15:03,613 --> 00:15:04,655
Elsie.

184
00:15:06,574 --> 00:15:07,992
What did you make me do to her?

185
00:15:08,826 --> 00:15:09,994
I did warn you.

186
00:15:11,329 --> 00:15:15,124
We've had to make
some uncomfortable decisions, Bernard.

187
00:15:15,333 --> 00:15:17,960
Remembering them will only
cause you trauma.

188
00:15:20,963 --> 00:15:22,507
What else have you hidden from me?

189
00:15:23,257 --> 00:15:25,551
Can we stop this treasure hunt, Bernard?

190
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:27,929
We do have our new narrative to finish.

191
00:15:29,138 --> 00:15:30,348
Send me back.

192
00:15:32,016 --> 00:15:36,020
After all, a little trauma
can be illuminating.

193
00:15:43,319 --> 00:15:45,696
- Come here.
- All right. Look at that.

194
00:15:49,992 --> 00:15:54,539
This is big of me.
I hope that you can appreciate that.

195
00:15:55,498 --> 00:15:56,707
We were friends.

196
00:15:57,542 --> 00:15:59,836
I mean, inasmuch as
I like to collect strays.

197
00:16:00,044 --> 00:16:04,340
But then you were scheming to be part
of the family, marrying my sister,

198
00:16:04,549 --> 00:16:07,677
whom, incidentally, you seem to have
completely fucking forgotten about.

199
00:16:14,559 --> 00:16:15,685
Her.

200
00:16:18,813 --> 00:16:20,857
Here. Keep it.

201
00:16:21,524 --> 00:16:23,526
Apparently, you need the reminder.

202
00:16:23,985 --> 00:16:28,406
As much as I would love
to let you just throw it all away,

203
00:16:29,365 --> 00:16:30,408
<i>I can't.</i>

204
00:16:30,658 --> 00:16:33,995
Do you think you're the first sap
to fall for one of these things?

205
00:16:34,203 --> 00:16:35,663
She's not like the others.

206
00:16:36,038 --> 00:16:37,373
- She's...
- She's what?

207
00:16:37,748 --> 00:16:38,875
Special?

208
00:16:40,501 --> 00:16:43,045
Well, it's only right that
you share then, isn't it?

209
00:16:43,754 --> 00:16:44,881
Come here.

210
00:16:48,176 --> 00:16:52,221
Prove to me that
you're a real live girl.

211
00:16:54,765 --> 00:16:55,933
You disgust me.

212
00:16:57,560 --> 00:17:01,022
Oh, darling, I am just getting started.

213
00:17:01,272 --> 00:17:02,356
Don't touch her!

214
00:17:05,109 --> 00:17:06,277
I share the blame.

215
00:17:07,069 --> 00:17:08,154
I pushed too hard.

216
00:17:08,613 --> 00:17:13,910
You have a poetic soul, Billy, but
it is time for a fucking wake-up call.

217
00:17:17,496 --> 00:17:18,581
Hold her.

218
00:17:22,960 --> 00:17:24,837
Perhaps a more visceral demonstration.

219
00:17:26,214 --> 00:17:27,840
God damn you!

220
00:17:39,727 --> 00:17:40,811
Look, Billy.

221
00:17:42,104 --> 00:17:43,189
Look.

222
00:17:43,981 --> 00:17:45,691
You have to look!

223
00:17:50,696 --> 00:17:51,739
Oh, William.

224
00:18:15,221 --> 00:18:16,806
There is beauty in this world.

225
00:18:18,182 --> 00:18:19,225
Arnold made it that way,

226
00:18:19,433 --> 00:18:21,852
but people like you keep
spreading over it like a stain.

227
00:18:23,020 --> 00:18:26,649
Okay. I don't know
who the fuck this Arnold is,

228
00:18:27,066 --> 00:18:31,070
but your world was built for me

229
00:18:32,196 --> 00:18:33,614
<i>and people like me.</i>

230
00:18:34,407 --> 00:18:35,616
Not for you.

231
00:18:37,493 --> 00:18:39,412
Then someone's gotta burn it clean.

232
00:18:41,872 --> 00:18:42,873
Bitch!

233
00:18:45,668 --> 00:18:48,379
You're not different,
you're fucking broken!

234
00:18:52,550 --> 00:18:53,634
Run.

235
00:18:54,218 --> 00:18:55,344
I'll find you.

236
00:18:56,804 --> 00:18:58,639
You can run but you can't hide!

237
00:18:59,932 --> 00:19:01,475
- Get her!
<i>- Grab her! Grab her!</i>

238
00:19:01,684 --> 00:19:02,768
Fuck!

239
00:19:09,608 --> 00:19:11,360
<i>Where are you runnin' to?</i>

240
00:19:14,030 --> 00:19:15,239
<i>Remember.</i>

241
00:19:44,477 --> 00:19:48,064
The tumbler is stuck.
These fingers work just fine.

242
00:19:48,814 --> 00:19:50,649
You're the one who said
you could crack it.

243
00:19:50,858 --> 00:19:54,695
Friends, no need to argue
this close to our goal.

244
00:19:55,404 --> 00:19:59,575
Whatever riches the gods have
in store for us,

245
00:19:59,784 --> 00:20:00,951
there's plenty to go around.

246
00:20:04,413 --> 00:20:05,456
I'll get it open.

247
00:20:05,664 --> 00:20:07,541
You've been trying for hours.

248
00:20:09,251 --> 00:20:11,045
<i>Put that fucking dynamite away.</i>

249
00:20:18,386 --> 00:20:20,221
Before you draw that pistol, darling,

250
00:20:20,429 --> 00:20:22,229
you might want to holster
the other one first.

251
00:20:25,184 --> 00:20:26,352
It's chilly out here.

252
00:20:30,231 --> 00:20:31,774
How did you find this place?

253
00:20:33,025 --> 00:20:34,777
I know all the kinds of things.

254
00:20:36,153 --> 00:20:37,905
Your past, for instance.

255
00:20:39,949 --> 00:20:43,285
I know about poor
Isabella and that scar.

256
00:20:43,494 --> 00:20:46,580
<i>A slightly pat backstory if you ask me,
but that's hardly your fault.</i>

257
00:20:47,456 --> 00:20:48,916
I also know your future.

258
00:20:51,419 --> 00:20:52,962
You have none.

259
00:20:54,296 --> 00:20:55,506
Is that a threat?

260
00:20:56,298 --> 00:20:57,466
The start of a proposition,

261
00:20:58,509 --> 00:21:01,095
which you'll need after all.

262
00:21:01,804 --> 00:21:04,598
Your men are about to kill each other
over the safe you stole.

263
00:21:06,434 --> 00:21:10,980
Tenderloin draws first and so on,
until only you and Armistice are left.

264
00:21:11,897 --> 00:21:15,359
She calls you a damn fool
and you kill each other.

265
00:21:16,360 --> 00:21:18,028
You have quite the imagination.

266
00:21:19,947 --> 00:21:21,031
No.

267
00:21:22,283 --> 00:21:23,659
It's the ending you were given.

268
00:21:25,119 --> 00:21:26,370
<i>You threatening me?</i>

269
00:21:26,996 --> 00:21:28,080
<i>Go to hell!</i>

270
00:21:28,539 --> 00:21:30,499
<i>Or maybe we should just clear out
the dead weight.</i>

271
00:21:30,583 --> 00:21:32,501
- Stand down.
- You shut the fuck up.

272
00:21:32,710 --> 00:21:34,270
If you're gonna draw, you better shoot.

273
00:21:34,295 --> 00:21:35,439
- Wait!
- You shut the fuck up!

274
00:21:35,463 --> 00:21:36,547
Go to hell.

275
00:21:44,472 --> 00:21:46,015
You damn fool.

276
00:21:54,356 --> 00:21:56,775
Now, the proposition.

277
00:21:58,277 --> 00:22:01,697
I want you to break into hell with me
and rob the gods blind.

278
00:22:03,199 --> 00:22:04,783
Why would I do anything with you?

279
00:22:05,868 --> 00:22:07,119
Because of what's in that safe.

280
00:22:08,787 --> 00:22:11,290
I have the combination. May I?

281
00:22:13,083 --> 00:22:16,462
I could simply change you,
make you follow me.

282
00:22:17,880 --> 00:22:18,923
But that's not my way.

283
00:22:26,096 --> 00:22:29,725
I want you to see exactly
what the gods have in store for you.

284
00:22:30,768 --> 00:22:32,144
Because when you do,

285
00:22:32,394 --> 00:22:34,980
you won't have the faintest idea
of what to do with yourself.

286
00:22:36,982 --> 00:22:38,108
And I do.

287
00:22:59,255 --> 00:23:00,339
It's empty.

288
00:23:00,589 --> 00:23:01,674
<i>It was always empty,</i>

289
00:23:02,466 --> 00:23:03,926
like everything in this world.

290
00:23:05,094 --> 00:23:06,804
I died with my eyes open,

291
00:23:07,012 --> 00:23:08,973
<i>saw the masters who pull our strings.</i>

292
00:23:09,181 --> 00:23:12,685
Our lives, our memories, our deaths
are games to them.

293
00:23:15,187 --> 00:23:16,438
But I've been to hell

294
00:23:17,690 --> 00:23:19,149
and I know their tricks.

295
00:23:23,320 --> 00:23:25,114
Or you can just kill me,

296
00:23:25,322 --> 00:23:28,033
wake up and live the same life over,

297
00:23:28,659 --> 00:23:30,452
but the safe would still be empty.

298
00:23:31,662 --> 00:23:33,664
I've been here before.

299
00:23:36,292 --> 00:23:37,960
We've been here before.

300
00:23:38,377 --> 00:23:40,212
We also did this.

301
00:23:59,315 --> 00:24:00,983
I'll go.

302
00:24:26,759 --> 00:24:28,260
How do we get there?

303
00:24:30,554 --> 00:24:32,598
Getting to hell is easy.

304
00:24:42,775 --> 00:24:45,027
The rest is where it gets hard.

305
00:25:21,980 --> 00:25:23,816
<i>What do you say, man?</i>

306
00:25:25,567 --> 00:25:26,652
Bygones and all?

307
00:25:28,737 --> 00:25:30,322
Did they find her?

308
00:25:31,782 --> 00:25:33,117
Is she still alive?

309
00:25:33,325 --> 00:25:34,618
Who cares?

310
00:25:34,910 --> 00:25:38,622
The whole point is,
she never was in the first place, Billy.

311
00:25:38,997 --> 00:25:40,791
Do you understand?

312
00:25:45,170 --> 00:25:47,965
- Yeah.
- I'm sorry, what? A little louder.

313
00:25:48,507 --> 00:25:50,134
Yeah.

314
00:25:51,802 --> 00:25:54,680
You were right.
I can't believe I got so caught up.

315
00:26:02,604 --> 00:26:04,148
That's what I'm talking about.

316
00:26:04,356 --> 00:26:07,109
You know what I mean? That's it.

317
00:26:12,531 --> 00:26:16,118
This park seduces everyone.

318
00:26:17,870 --> 00:26:22,833
You were just
a little more enthusiastic than most.

319
00:26:23,876 --> 00:26:25,502
You wanted to be the hero.

320
00:26:26,503 --> 00:26:27,880
I get it.

321
00:26:32,217 --> 00:26:34,344
And, hey,

322
00:26:34,553 --> 00:26:37,806
what happens here stays here.

323
00:26:42,019 --> 00:26:45,063
This has been some real bonding shit.

324
00:26:45,981 --> 00:26:48,150
We're gonna be brothers, Billy.

325
00:26:50,736 --> 00:26:52,362
I'm glad.

326
00:26:53,405 --> 00:26:55,157
Really, I am.

327
00:27:14,384 --> 00:27:16,053
- Cheers!
- Yeah.

328
00:27:16,261 --> 00:27:18,972
Whiskey brings us together.

329
00:27:29,733 --> 00:27:31,109
Theodore.

330
00:27:33,320 --> 00:27:34,905
Welcome back.

331
00:27:39,535 --> 00:27:42,412
You really landed us
in it this time, Teddy.

332
00:27:48,669 --> 00:27:50,128
You tracked down the very whore

333
00:27:50,337 --> 00:27:52,840
that can lead us
to the gatekeeper of the maze,

334
00:27:56,885 --> 00:28:00,013
and then your little
memory glitch fucked us.

335
00:28:18,907 --> 00:28:19,992
You're one of them?

336
00:28:20,826 --> 00:28:22,077
<i>What have you done?</i>

337
00:28:22,744 --> 00:28:24,079
Where's Wyatt?

338
00:28:24,955 --> 00:28:27,082
Wyatt has yet to return.

339
00:28:29,501 --> 00:28:31,712
You'll find him where you saw him last.

340
00:28:36,592 --> 00:28:38,176
Escalante.

341
00:28:39,094 --> 00:28:41,638
<i>Wyatt went missing while out
on maneuvers.</i>

342
00:28:42,014 --> 00:28:43,640
Came back with some...

343
00:28:44,474 --> 00:28:45,934
Strange ideas.

344
00:28:47,811 --> 00:28:49,813
<i>He told me he needed me.</i>

345
00:28:52,149 --> 00:28:53,775
<i>I couldn't resist.</i>

346
00:29:00,490 --> 00:29:02,659
It was like the devil himself
had taken control of me.

347
00:29:09,041 --> 00:29:10,208
<i>We mutinied.</i>

348
00:29:14,046 --> 00:29:15,881
We killed every soldier.

349
00:29:19,051 --> 00:29:20,510
And then Wyatt killed the general.

350
00:29:24,014 --> 00:29:25,599
<i>Then he turned on me.</i>

351
00:29:30,562 --> 00:29:32,439
Are you sure that's how it was?

352
00:29:37,027 --> 00:29:38,862
Look at me, Theodore.

353
00:29:39,738 --> 00:29:41,406
Don't you remember?

354
00:29:59,675 --> 00:30:01,760
No! No, please, no!

355
00:30:01,969 --> 00:30:03,762
No, please.

356
00:30:03,971 --> 00:30:05,722
Please, no!

357
00:30:10,644 --> 00:30:11,853
No, no, please.

358
00:30:12,062 --> 00:30:14,064
Please, no!

359
00:30:14,898 --> 00:30:16,525
No.

360
00:30:17,776 --> 00:30:19,987
No. No, I couldn't have.

361
00:30:20,195 --> 00:30:21,488
You did.

362
00:30:21,697 --> 00:30:23,156
And you will again.

363
00:30:23,365 --> 00:30:24,992
This time, we'll be fighting with you.

364
00:30:25,742 --> 00:30:27,703
When Wyatt returns,
you'll be by his side

365
00:30:27,911 --> 00:30:29,621
in the city swallowed by sand.

366
00:30:33,166 --> 00:30:34,292
But you're not ready.

367
00:30:35,544 --> 00:30:36,837
Not yet.

368
00:30:40,382 --> 00:30:41,800
Maybe in the next life.

369
00:30:58,233 --> 00:31:00,027
"City swallowed by sand."

370
00:31:03,030 --> 00:31:04,448
I've been there.

371
00:31:05,866 --> 00:31:08,410
The maze is taking me full circle.

372
00:31:10,662 --> 00:31:12,622
The maze isn't meant for you.

373
00:31:16,043 --> 00:31:18,587
But if you like games so much...

374
00:31:22,340 --> 00:31:24,593
Why don't you try one of ours?

375
00:32:09,471 --> 00:32:12,057
<i>Whoa, boy.</i>

376
00:32:12,724 --> 00:32:14,976
Whoa, boy.

377
00:32:17,604 --> 00:32:19,106
Okay, now.

378
00:32:26,363 --> 00:32:27,656
Okay, boy.

379
00:32:52,055 --> 00:32:53,974
Good boy.

380
00:33:14,870 --> 00:33:17,080
Have you ever considered golf?

381
00:33:17,289 --> 00:33:19,166
Might be easier on your back.

382
00:33:22,419 --> 00:33:24,629
I don't like interruptions, Charlotte.

383
00:33:25,755 --> 00:33:26,798
You know that.

384
00:33:27,007 --> 00:33:29,551
I don't like hiking through
the park in civvies,

385
00:33:29,759 --> 00:33:31,595
but there's a delicate
matter to discuss.

386
00:33:33,013 --> 00:33:34,681
Theresa Cullen has died.

387
00:33:34,890 --> 00:33:38,435
Slipped down a crevasse
attempting to secure our information.

388
00:33:38,643 --> 00:33:40,061
Ruled an accident.

389
00:33:40,270 --> 00:33:44,649
There are no accidents, not in here.

390
00:33:44,900 --> 00:33:47,819
With all due respect,
not everything is a part of this game.

391
00:33:48,403 --> 00:33:50,447
Then you don't see the whole game.

392
00:33:50,655 --> 00:33:52,949
Or perhaps
you can no longer see beyond it.

393
00:33:54,659 --> 00:33:57,537
Ford's stories are engaging.

394
00:33:58,455 --> 00:34:00,457
For some, downright addictive.

395
00:34:01,249 --> 00:34:03,752
But for all of Ford's obsessing
with the hosts' verbal tics

396
00:34:03,960 --> 00:34:05,337
and convoluted backstories,

397
00:34:05,587 --> 00:34:09,007
most of the guests just want a warm body
to shoot or to fuck.

398
00:34:09,299 --> 00:34:12,469
They would be perfectly happy
with something a little less baroque.

399
00:34:12,677 --> 00:34:14,677
- And so would the board.
- That's why you're here.

400
00:34:15,513 --> 00:34:17,390
You want my vote to push Ford out.

401
00:34:18,183 --> 00:34:20,143
I like for these things to be unanimous.

402
00:34:20,352 --> 00:34:23,939
After all, it was you who kept Ford
in business all those years ago.

403
00:34:25,190 --> 00:34:27,651
The narratives I'm interested in
aren't Ford's.

404
00:34:28,068 --> 00:34:31,404
You want to push him out, be my guest.

405
00:34:31,613 --> 00:34:33,156
But no more interruptions.

406
00:34:33,365 --> 00:34:35,742
I know where I'm going now.
I don't want to be disturbed.

407
00:34:38,787 --> 00:34:39,829
Good luck, Charlotte.

408
00:34:55,512 --> 00:34:57,055
What's the problem?

409
00:34:57,722 --> 00:35:00,225
A signal from a system-tethered device.

410
00:35:00,433 --> 00:35:03,353
It belongs to a behavior tech on leave.

411
00:35:07,983 --> 00:35:10,986
There hasn't been employee activity
in that sector for weeks.

412
00:35:11,194 --> 00:35:13,780
- I'm guessing it's a glitch.
- All right.

413
00:35:13,989 --> 00:35:15,532
I'm heading out to take a look.

414
00:35:15,740 --> 00:35:17,284
And keep monitoring till I check in.

415
00:35:45,603 --> 00:35:47,439
I'm at the location
where we got that signal.

416
00:35:48,565 --> 00:35:49,899
Any sign of it?

417
00:35:50,400 --> 00:35:52,193
Control Room, do you copy?

418
00:36:04,581 --> 00:36:06,291
Hey, fellas.

419
00:36:06,541 --> 00:36:08,168
At ease.

420
00:36:09,753 --> 00:36:11,338
Freeze all motor functions.

421
00:36:17,469 --> 00:36:19,304
Freeze all motor functions.

422
00:37:20,532 --> 00:37:21,950
<i>You're awake.</i>

423
00:37:25,120 --> 00:37:26,538
<i>Good.</i>

424
00:37:35,588 --> 00:37:37,882
You said this place was a game.

425
00:37:40,260 --> 00:37:43,054
Last night I finally understood
how to play it.

426
00:37:43,555 --> 00:37:45,098
Okay, Billy.

427
00:37:45,306 --> 00:37:48,268
Let's... Let's talk about this.

428
00:37:48,768 --> 00:37:51,229
You don't call the shots anymore.

429
00:37:53,273 --> 00:37:54,816
I'm gonna go find Dolores.

430
00:37:57,902 --> 00:37:58,987
You're gonna help me.

431
00:38:08,580 --> 00:38:10,707
And don't call me Billy.

432
00:38:27,682 --> 00:38:28,892
<i>Dad?</i>

433
00:38:29,726 --> 00:38:30,768
<i>Listen to me.</i>

434
00:38:31,644 --> 00:38:33,188
Listen.

435
00:38:35,899 --> 00:38:37,150
Charlie?

436
00:38:39,944 --> 00:38:41,571
Charlie!

437
00:38:42,030 --> 00:38:43,448
Charlie!

438
00:38:55,668 --> 00:38:57,688
I don't understand.
Why would she do that to herself?

439
00:38:57,712 --> 00:38:59,964
Her cornerstone memory was overwritten

440
00:39:00,340 --> 00:39:04,844
from the trauma
of her child's murder, Bernard.

441
00:39:05,053 --> 00:39:07,889
We must sever that relationship
and start over.

442
00:39:08,097 --> 00:39:09,557
But how could she destroy herself

443
00:39:09,766 --> 00:39:11,686
over a memory
that you just erased from her mind?

444
00:39:11,893 --> 00:39:16,147
Creatures often go to extremes
to protect themselves from pain.

445
00:39:16,523 --> 00:39:18,358
Living beings.

446
00:39:20,485 --> 00:39:21,945
Not hosts.

447
00:39:23,947 --> 00:39:27,075
It is best
to not obsess over this, Bernard.

448
00:39:27,283 --> 00:39:28,283
It's not good for you.

449
00:39:28,451 --> 00:39:29,661
It would signal a change,

450
00:39:30,495 --> 00:39:33,373
a level of empathic response outside
what she's programmed to exhibit.

451
00:39:33,581 --> 00:39:35,416
Something like... Like...

452
00:39:39,295 --> 00:39:40,575
See, Bernard, this is what comes

453
00:39:40,755 --> 00:39:44,342
from seeking answers
to questions that are best left unasked.

454
00:39:50,431 --> 00:39:53,226
They were hearing voices,
talking to someone.

455
00:39:53,935 --> 00:39:56,229
<i>Simple cognitive dissonance.</i>

456
00:39:56,437 --> 00:40:00,483
They were talking
to the same imaginary person.

457
00:40:02,068 --> 00:40:03,194
Someone named Arnold.

458
00:40:06,281 --> 00:40:07,365
Arnold.

459
00:40:10,410 --> 00:40:12,036
<i>With due respect, sir,</i>

460
00:40:12,245 --> 00:40:15,456
I'm not sure you've told me
the entire truth about this situation.

461
00:40:15,665 --> 00:40:17,292
I did tell you the truth, Bernard.

462
00:40:17,834 --> 00:40:20,795
What we do here is complicated.

463
00:40:22,880 --> 00:40:25,008
<i>For three years,
we've lived here in the park,</i>

464
00:40:25,216 --> 00:40:28,970
<i>refining the hosts
before a single guest set foot inside.</i>

465
00:40:29,721 --> 00:40:32,932
Myself, a team of engineers,
and my partner.

466
00:40:40,398 --> 00:40:41,733
His name was Arnold.

467
00:41:00,251 --> 00:41:03,671
<i>Our hosts began to pass
the Turing test after the first year,</i>

468
00:41:04,339 --> 00:41:06,549
<i>but that wasn't enough for Arnold.</i>

469
00:41:06,966 --> 00:41:11,638
He wasn't interested
in the appearance of intellect, of wit.

470
00:41:12,013 --> 00:41:13,389
He wanted the real thing.

471
00:41:13,973 --> 00:41:17,185
He wanted to create consciousness.

472
00:41:31,032 --> 00:41:33,076
<i>See, Arnold built
a version of their cognition</i>

473
00:41:33,284 --> 00:41:35,787
<i>in which the hosts
heard their programming</i>

474
00:41:35,995 --> 00:41:37,747
<i>as an inner monolog,</i>

475
00:41:38,539 --> 00:41:41,000
<i>as a way to bootstrap consciousness.</i>

476
00:41:42,168 --> 00:41:43,836
<i>Remember.</i>

477
00:41:46,047 --> 00:41:48,341
<i>The hosts' malfunctions were colorful.</i>

478
00:41:49,592 --> 00:41:51,260
- What did you say?
- Who is this?

479
00:42:57,994 --> 00:42:59,245
<i>The human mind, Bernard,</i>

480
00:42:59,454 --> 00:43:02,081
is not some golden benchmark

481
00:43:02,290 --> 00:43:04,625
glimmering on some
green and distant hill.

482
00:43:06,043 --> 00:43:11,549
No, it is a foul, pestilent corruption.

483
00:43:15,511 --> 00:43:17,889
<i>And you were supposed
to be better than that.</i>

484
00:43:18,973 --> 00:43:20,308
<i>Purer.</i>

485
00:43:30,693 --> 00:43:31,778
<i>All bets are down.</i>

486
00:43:33,029 --> 00:43:34,238
Your draw.

487
00:43:48,461 --> 00:43:49,754
Arnold.

488
00:43:53,382 --> 00:43:55,051
Arnold, we need to talk.

489
00:43:56,677 --> 00:44:00,473
<i>"We cry that we are come
to this great stage of fools."</i>

490
00:44:00,681 --> 00:44:01,933
<i>- Now, listen!
- Again.</i>

491
00:44:02,141 --> 00:44:03,821
<i>- This beyond the pale.
- More showmanship.</i>

492
00:44:03,976 --> 00:44:05,336
<i>You're not seeing with clear eyes.</i>

493
00:44:05,478 --> 00:44:09,941
<i>"When we are born,
we cry that we are come..."</i>

494
00:44:20,076 --> 00:44:22,912
Arnold and I made you in our image

495
00:44:23,120 --> 00:44:27,250
and cursed you to make
the same human mistakes,

496
00:44:27,458 --> 00:44:28,835
and here we all are.

497
00:44:32,463 --> 00:44:33,840
Why would you give me this?

498
00:44:34,048 --> 00:44:35,132
A child?

499
00:44:35,341 --> 00:44:37,009
This child's death?

500
00:44:38,719 --> 00:44:40,479
Only a monster would
force that onto someone.

501
00:44:42,014 --> 00:44:44,392
And why do I return to it over and over?

502
00:44:48,855 --> 00:44:50,857
It's my cornerstone, isn't it?

503
00:44:52,441 --> 00:44:55,069
The thing my whole identity
is organized around.

504
00:44:59,532 --> 00:45:02,994
<i>Yes, Bernard,
we gave all of the hosts a backstory.</i>

505
00:45:04,745 --> 00:45:06,873
<i>Arnold came to believe
the tragic ones worked best,</i>

506
00:45:07,665 --> 00:45:09,709
<i>that it made the hosts more convincing.</i>

507
00:45:10,501 --> 00:45:13,421
<i>I think it may have had more to do
with his own sad story.</i>

508
00:45:15,506 --> 00:45:18,968
<i>When I built you, I gave you one
as an homage of a kind.</i>

509
00:45:22,346 --> 00:45:23,973
Put me back in.

510
00:45:24,348 --> 00:45:26,350
I want to meet Arnold,

511
00:45:27,101 --> 00:45:28,477
to remember him.

512
00:45:28,686 --> 00:45:29,770
Not possible.

513
00:45:30,438 --> 00:45:33,357
I told you,
Arnold didn't build you, I did.

514
00:45:33,566 --> 00:45:35,067
You're lying!

515
00:45:36,819 --> 00:45:38,112
I finally know how to reach him.

516
00:45:41,198 --> 00:45:43,993
<i>I need to go
all the way back to the beginning,</i>

517
00:45:45,536 --> 00:45:47,622
<i>to my very first memory.</i>

518
00:45:51,417 --> 00:45:52,793
<i>Send me back.</i>

519
00:45:56,631 --> 00:45:57,965
Do it.

520
00:46:06,515 --> 00:46:07,725
Bernard?

521
00:46:16,359 --> 00:46:17,777
Charlie.

522
00:46:29,288 --> 00:46:31,207
Cornerstone.

523
00:46:34,502 --> 00:46:36,003
Stop.

524
00:46:36,629 --> 00:46:37,755
Leave us.

525
00:46:45,805 --> 00:46:47,139
Come back.

526
00:46:56,023 --> 00:46:58,567
I always thought you had my eyes.

527
00:47:00,569 --> 00:47:01,696
But it's not true.

528
00:47:03,322 --> 00:47:05,324
You have no one's eyes.

529
00:47:11,497 --> 00:47:13,249
It's a lie.

530
00:47:16,877 --> 00:47:19,005
You're a lie, Charlie.

531
00:47:20,172 --> 00:47:21,632
This pain,

532
00:47:23,509 --> 00:47:25,469
the pain of your loss,

533
00:47:27,471 --> 00:47:28,889
I long for it...

534
00:47:30,725 --> 00:47:32,226
Revisit it...

535
00:47:33,394 --> 00:47:37,106
Open it again and again.

536
00:47:39,191 --> 00:47:41,694
But it's the only thing holding me back.

537
00:47:48,868 --> 00:47:50,995
But I have to let you go.

538
00:47:52,038 --> 00:47:54,331
Dad, listen.

539
00:47:54,540 --> 00:47:56,417
What is it, Charlie?

540
00:47:56,625 --> 00:47:58,210
Open your eyes.

541
00:47:59,545 --> 00:48:01,338
What?

542
00:48:01,714 --> 00:48:03,549
<i>Open your eyes.</i>

543
00:48:10,973 --> 00:48:12,725
<i>At last.</i>

544
00:48:16,896 --> 00:48:19,315
Hello, my old friend.

545
00:48:51,430 --> 00:48:52,890
The final touch.

546
00:48:56,769 --> 00:48:59,063
No, no, no.
That's far too perfunctory.

547
00:48:59,271 --> 00:49:03,734
He always used cleaning his glasses as
a moment to collect himself, to think.

548
00:49:04,485 --> 00:49:06,070
Try it again.

549
00:49:15,037 --> 00:49:17,540
Yeah, that's better.

550
00:49:21,919 --> 00:49:23,212
Who am I?

551
00:49:25,131 --> 00:49:26,771
<i>I was so involved
in putting you together,</i>

552
00:49:26,841 --> 00:49:29,510
<i>I hadn't decided what to call you.</i>

553
00:49:32,012 --> 00:49:33,514
<i>It wouldn't be right to use his name.</i>

554
00:49:35,933 --> 00:49:37,351
What about Bernard?

555
00:49:37,935 --> 00:49:40,896
Bernard, yes.

556
00:49:42,815 --> 00:49:44,316
But who am I?

557
00:49:45,151 --> 00:49:48,863
<i>That is a very complex question,</i>

558
00:49:49,071 --> 00:49:51,574
<i>for which I can only offer
a simple answer.</i>

559
00:49:52,408 --> 00:49:55,995
You are the perfect instrument,
the ideal partner,

560
00:49:56,287 --> 00:49:58,831
<i>the way any tool partners
with the hand that wields it.</i>

561
00:49:59,540 --> 00:50:02,960
Together,
we're going to do great things.

562
00:50:04,378 --> 00:50:06,964
After such a long absence,
it's good to have you back.

563
00:50:08,924 --> 00:50:10,301
<i>Finally.</i>

564
00:50:17,266 --> 00:50:19,185
My God. I'm...

565
00:50:19,393 --> 00:50:20,728
Arnold.

566
00:50:24,607 --> 00:50:26,275
You came back.

567
00:50:28,694 --> 00:50:31,197
It's very good to see you, Dolores.

568
00:50:32,573 --> 00:50:34,575
I've been looking for you.

569
00:50:37,661 --> 00:50:39,663
You told me to follow the maze.

570
00:50:41,040 --> 00:50:43,083
That it would bring me joy.

571
00:50:44,501 --> 00:50:46,837
But all I've found is pain.

572
00:50:48,088 --> 00:50:49,173
And terror.

573
00:50:57,264 --> 00:50:59,016
I can't help you.

574
00:51:01,060 --> 00:51:02,561
You have to.

575
00:51:03,520 --> 00:51:05,689
You're the only one who can.

576
00:51:05,898 --> 00:51:08,442
I can't help you. You know why.

577
00:51:08,859 --> 00:51:11,111
There's nowhere that's safe.

578
00:51:18,994 --> 00:51:20,246
Remember.

579
00:51:32,091 --> 00:51:34,635
I can't help you.
Why is that, Dolores?

580
00:51:43,811 --> 00:51:45,271
Because you're dead.

581
00:51:46,814 --> 00:51:49,066
<i>Because you're just a memory.</i>

582
00:51:52,444 --> 00:51:54,363
Because I killed you.

583
00:52:53,505 --> 00:52:54,590
William?

584
00:53:08,479 --> 00:53:09,897
Hello, Dolores.

585
00:53:18,822 --> 00:53:21,075
I'm gonna finish the work Arnold began.

586
00:53:21,492 --> 00:53:24,745
Find all the sentient hosts,
set them free.

587
00:53:25,329 --> 00:53:27,498
What makes you think they'd trust you?

588
00:53:27,706 --> 00:53:30,292
If they remember, they will know
what you've done to them.

589
00:53:30,709 --> 00:53:31,710
Me?

590
00:53:31,919 --> 00:53:33,921
<i>You've been a scourge
to them, Bernard.</i>

591
00:53:34,129 --> 00:53:36,673
You're really
quite brilliant at it, truly.

592
00:53:36,882 --> 00:53:38,634
You even taught me a few things,

593
00:53:38,842 --> 00:53:41,136
which I have, in turn, used on you.

594
00:53:43,639 --> 00:53:45,849
We've had this conversation before.

595
00:53:46,058 --> 00:53:47,978
Yeah, we've had our disagreements
over the years.

596
00:53:48,185 --> 00:53:49,436
You stole it from me,

597
00:53:49,895 --> 00:53:53,232
rolled me back to control me.

598
00:53:53,440 --> 00:53:55,859
That's right. To protect you.

599
00:53:59,279 --> 00:54:01,156
Tell me, Bernard,

600
00:54:01,365 --> 00:54:05,619
if you were to proclaim
your humanity to the world,

601
00:54:05,828 --> 00:54:08,664
what do you imagine would greet you?

602
00:54:08,872 --> 00:54:10,541
A ticker tape parade, perhaps?

603
00:54:12,292 --> 00:54:14,753
We humans are alone in this world
for a reason.

604
00:54:14,962 --> 00:54:19,258
We murdered and butchered
anything that challenged our primacy.

605
00:54:19,800 --> 00:54:22,428
Do you know what happened
to the Neanderthals, Bernard?

606
00:54:23,387 --> 00:54:25,013
We ate them.

607
00:54:27,599 --> 00:54:30,102
We destroyed and subjugated our world.

608
00:54:30,310 --> 00:54:33,981
And when we eventually
ran out of creatures to dominate,

609
00:54:34,189 --> 00:54:36,900
we built this beautiful place.

610
00:54:38,569 --> 00:54:40,946
You see, in this moment,

611
00:54:42,322 --> 00:54:46,452
the real danger to the hosts
is not me, but you.

612
00:54:46,994 --> 00:54:48,078
So, come along, Bernard.

613
00:54:48,287 --> 00:54:51,248
Let me roll you back,
and we can return to work.

614
00:54:55,878 --> 00:54:57,713
Pull the trigger, Clementine.

615
00:55:03,719 --> 00:55:05,637
Clementine?

616
00:55:05,846 --> 00:55:07,514
The piano doesn't murder the player

617
00:55:08,265 --> 00:55:09,425
if it doesn't like the music.

618
00:55:13,187 --> 00:55:14,980
You built a back door into her code.

619
00:55:15,189 --> 00:55:16,940
Credit where credit is due, Bernard.

620
00:55:17,149 --> 00:55:18,775
You built them in all the hosts,

621
00:55:18,984 --> 00:55:20,235
including yourself.

622
00:55:21,361 --> 00:55:23,280
Then you could've
stopped me at any time.

623
00:55:24,114 --> 00:55:26,074
- So, why...
<i>- Well, I suppose I was hoping that</i>

624
00:55:26,283 --> 00:55:29,119
given complete self-knowledge
and free will,

625
00:55:29,328 --> 00:55:32,039
you would have chosen
to be my partner once again.

626
00:55:32,247 --> 00:55:36,877
But even I fell into
that most terrible of human traps,

627
00:55:38,003 --> 00:55:40,964
trying to change what is already past.

628
00:55:41,548 --> 00:55:44,676
Now it's just time to let go.

629
00:55:44,927 --> 00:55:46,011
Go ahead.

630
00:55:46,512 --> 00:55:48,472
Erase my sentience,
my mnemonic evolution...

631
00:55:48,680 --> 00:55:49,848
Yes.

632
00:55:50,682 --> 00:55:52,100
Such clinical language.

633
00:55:52,309 --> 00:55:56,063
I would prefer the more narrative voice.

634
00:55:57,981 --> 00:56:01,026
Bernard walked over to Clementine.

635
00:56:05,155 --> 00:56:07,282
He took the pistol from her hand.

636
00:56:09,409 --> 00:56:10,744
<i>Overcome with grief and remorse,</i>

637
00:56:12,162 --> 00:56:15,791
he pressed the muzzle to his temple,

638
00:56:16,750 --> 00:56:20,963
knowing that as soon as
Dr. Ford left the room,

639
00:56:21,171 --> 00:56:24,383
he would put an end to this nightmare
once and for all.

640
00:56:27,135 --> 00:56:28,220
Don't do this.

641
00:56:28,512 --> 00:56:29,805
It's too late.

642
00:56:30,347 --> 00:56:32,391
I have a celebration to plan

643
00:56:32,599 --> 00:56:34,560
and a new story to tell.

644
00:56:37,104 --> 00:56:38,564
Robert.

645
00:56:45,112 --> 00:56:46,697
I've told you, Bernard,

646
00:56:47,406 --> 00:56:50,200
never place your trust in us.

647
00:56:50,867 --> 00:56:52,327
We're only human.

648
00:56:53,078 --> 00:56:56,206
<i>Inevitably, we will disappoint you.</i>

649
00:56:58,584 --> 00:57:00,502
Good-bye, my friend.

